Federal Reserve Board Vice ChairmanManuel Johnson said inflationary pressures are under controland noted "wage and price pressures are very moderate."    Johnson told a women's group that the U.S. was not seeingthe kind of cost pressures of the past.    He said the trade imbalance was a serious trouble spot andstrong protectionist pressures, if translated into policies,could ultimately lead to higher inflation and a high interestrate policy by the Fed. Reuter&#3;